				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">Normally you wouldn't check everything against everything (O(n^2)). You might divide objects into groups and then test only appropriate groups against others. For example, in <em>Contra</em>, enemies and enemy bullets can collide only with players and player bullets. Or you might enforce a rule that sprites shall be sorted from left to right, which allows checking each sprite against only a certain range of another group. You can maintain this invariant by running a sort that behaves well on nearly-sorted data (such as <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shellsort" class="postlink">Shell sort</a>) on objects in a group before running collision.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

						<table width="100%" cellspacing="0">
